-- China, Indonesia, Philippines, Thailand: Asian Bonds and Currency Preview
-- David Yong
-- 2010-07-19T22:32:12Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-19/china-indonesia-philippines-thailand-asian-bonds-and-currency-preview.html

          
          
             The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in Asia’s local bonds and
currencies today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the
previous trading session unless stated otherwise.  
 Japan: Chief Cabinet Secretary Yoshito Sengoku and Finance
Minister Yoshihiko Noda will hold media briefings after a
cabinet meeting in the morning.  
 The Cabinet Office will release at 2 p.m. in Tokyo its
final report on the coincident and leading indexes for May. The
coincident economic index fell to 101.2, based on a preliminary
assessment published on July 6. That would compare with a
reading of 101.3 in April.  
 The Ministry of Finance will announce at 10:30 a.m. in
Tokyo the amount of two-year Japanese government bonds it plans
to sell on July 27.  
 The yield on the 1.1 percent government bond due in June
2020 was 1.085 percent on July 16, according to Japan Bond
Trading Co., the nation’s largest interdealer debt broker.
Financial markets were closed yesterday for a public holiday.  
 The yen traded at 86.78 per dollar at 7:20 a.m. in Tokyo.  
 China: The central bank will today sell 45 billion yuan
($6.6 billion) of one-year bills. It sold similar-maturity debt
at 2.093 percent on July 13. The Export-Import Bank will sell 10
billion yuan of five-year debt. The lender last sold similar-
maturity debt on April 9 at 3.37 percent.  
 The yield on the 2.53 percent note due in June 2015 was
2.57 percent. The yuan was at 6.7788 per dollar.  
 Indonesia:  The government will today auction a total of 4
trillion rupiah ($441 million) of securities maturing 2015, 2021
and 2031. It will also sell bills due in one year.  
 The yield on the 11 percent bond due in November 2020 was
8.19 percent, according to the Inter Dealer Market Association.
The rupiah was at 9,064 per dollar.  
 Malaysia: The statistics department will release the
inflation data for June tomorrow. Consumer prices rose 1.7
percent from a year earlier, versus 1.6 percent in May,
according to the median forecast in a Bloomberg survey.  
 The yield on the 3.835 percent debt maturing in August 2015
was 3.36 percent, according to Bursa Malaysia. The ringgit was
at 3.2255 per dollar.  
 Philippines: The government will auction 8.5 billion pesos
($183 million) of seven-year bonds today. The securities yielded
7.03 percent at the previous sale on June 8.  
 The yield on the 7.75 percent debt due February 2020 was
7.50 percent. The peso was at 46.435 per dollar.  
 Singapore: The government will say on July 23 that
inflation accelerated 3.5 percent in June from a year earlier,
according to a Bloomberg News survey. Prices rose 3.2 percent in
May.  
 The yield on the 3.25 percent notes due September 2020 was
2.25 percent. The Singapore dollar was at S$1.3772.  
 Thailand: Exports increased 34.5 percent in June from a
year earlier after rising 42.1 percent in May, a government
report tomorrow will show, based on the median estimate in a
Bloomberg survey.  
 The yield on the 3.625 percent note due in May 2015 was
2.97 percent. The baht was at 32.26 per dollar.  
 To contact the reporter on this story:
